{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Nigam Arora", "text": "Published: Stocks will rise in the short term, but investors will be worse off in the long term By No politician in the United States wants Americans to be worse off and deliberately take steps that are bad for an average American investor. However the policy of destroying the dollar, though well-intentioned, will lead to American investors being worse off in the long term. In the short term, investors are celebrating a lower dollar. But it is also prudent to start thinking of defensive steps to preserve wealth. The dollar fell to a three-year low after comments by the Treasury Secretary Mnuchin on Wednesday in support of a weaker dollar. It was the biggest one-day fall in 10 months. Before his inauguration, President Trump declared that the dollar was too strong. This started the decline in the dollar. But Mnuchin\u2019s comment is like drilling a hole in a dam that is holding back a flood. Initially after the hole is drilled, only a small amount of water flows out. But if the hole is not repaired or more holes are drilled, pretty soon the dam loses its structural integrity and causes a flood. In this case if the flood happens, it will be average investors losing money in the stock market, like they did in 2008 and 2000. I am politically agnostic. My sole focus is to help investors. My longtime readers know that I have often expressed opinions that were unpopular at the time. To understand this minority opinion, let\u2019s start with a chart. Please for an annotated chart of the Dollar Index Bullish Fund that represents the dollar index Please note the following from the chart: \u2022 The major support is far below where it is trading now. This means from a technical perspective, there is still a lot of room for the dollar to fall farther. \u2022 Before the present fall, a pattern of lower lows was already established. \u2022 After lower lows, the rally failed. \u2022 Now there is another lower low after Treasury Secretary Mnuchin\u2019s comment. \u2022 Collectively all this paints a very bearish picture for the dollar. However in the short term the dollar is very oversold and a bounce up is typical.   In the short term, a weaker dollar is good for stocks, as the earnings of the companies that are in S&P 500 and Dow Jones Industrial Index go up. This is reflected in the moves in broad-based ETFs such as the SPDR S&P 500 ETF and the PowerShares QQQ  Earnings of popular tech stocks will also go up because they derive a significant portion of revenue from abroad. Examples of companies benefiting are Apple Facebook Alphabet  Netflix Nvidia and AMD     Gold and silver are priced in dollars. For this reason they generally move inversely to the dollar\u2019s moves. The SPDR Gold Shares ETF and the iShares Silver Trust ETF have moved up on the weaker dollar. Also moving up are ETFs for precious metal miners junior gold miners and leveraged gold miners  Just like gold, oil is also priced in dollars. When the dollar moves down, oil generally goes up. ETFs of interest are the U.S.Oil Fund and VelocityShares 3x Long Crude Oil ETNs  Here are the reasons why a lower dollar is bad for average American investors in the long term: \u2022 The dollar has been the world\u2019s reserve currency. This has allowed the U. S. to engage in both fiscal and monetary policies that have benefited American investors. A lower dollar endangers the reserve currency status. \u2022 Would you buy stock in a company where the management is actively seeking ways to lower the price of the stock? A country is no different. The United States government is actively seeking to lower the value of the dollar. Would you want to hold the dollar? \u2022 As other countries start questioning the value of holding the dollar, it will negatively impact the dollar\u2019s status as a reserve currency. \u2022 The United States is a highly indebted country. A large portion of the debt is financed by foreigners. Why would foreigners want to buy U.S. debt when the value of the dollar is falling? \u2022 If the demand by foreigners for buying the U.S. debt wanes, interest rates will go up. \u2022 The United States is a big importer. As the dollar weakens, the cost of the imports will go up. This will cause inflation. \u2022 Rapidly rising inflation is bad for the stock market. \u2022 To control rapidly rising inflation, the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates. \u2022 Rapidly rising interest rates are bad for the stock market. \u2022 Foreigners now buy a significant amount of U.S. stocks. With the dollar falling, foreigners will have less reason to buy U.S. stocks. This will be bad for the stock market. Investors ought to start thinking about assets that aren\u2019t dependent on the U. S. economy and also about assets that benefit from a lower dollar in the long term. I\u2019ll address this more in a future article.     Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/making-america-great-again-by-destroying-the-dollar-is-bad-for-the-average-american-investor-2018-01-25", "headline": "Making America great again by destroying the dollar is bad for the average U.S. investor - MarketWatch"}
{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Emily Bary", "text": "Published: The company\u2019s data-centric businesses grew 21% in the holiday quarter, while the PC business shrunk slightly By Intel Corp. shares rose more than 10% to its highest per-share prices since 2000 Friday, its largest one-day gain in almost nine years, after a strong earnings report led multiple analysts to raise their price targets. The chip giant late Thursday and also reported December-quarter revenue ahead of consensus estimates. Investors were also pleased to hear management say that to have \u201cany material impact\u201d on product costs, though the company updated its risk factors to include the possibility of the security exploits affecting results.   Analysts heaped praise on the company, particularly its cloud-focused businesses, and helped shares rise 10.6% to $50.08 at the close. At least 20 analysts boosted their price targets, though there were no upgrades as nearly two-thirds of analysts who cover the stock already rate it a buy, according to FactSet. \u201cWe continue to believe Intel\u2019s diversification toward data-centric businesses and continued focus on increasing operational efficiencies markets are driving the company toward faster longer-term revenue growth at stronger profitability margins,\u201d wrote MKM Partners analyst Ruben Roy, who upped his price target to $55 from $50. The company\u2019s data-centric businesses accounted for 47% of Intel\u2019s total revenue in the latest quarter after posting 21% revenue growth, while the firm\u2019s PC-centric businesses witnessed a small decline. CFO Robert Swan said on the earnings conference call that Intel expects midteens growth for the data-centric segment over the course of the year. \u201cWe see continued positive trends as Xeon Scalable (Skylake) is at the early stages of its product ramp,\u201d JP Morgan analyst Harlan Sur wrote in commenting on the data-center business. He also raised his price target on the stock to $55, from $53 previously. Sur added: \u201cWe see the team continuing to drive outsized growth in non-PC segments (especially data center as cloud service provider spending is estimated to grow at a 20%+ CAGR over the next few years), continuing to expand its presence in new markets and drive margin expansion higher over the next few years.\u201d Susquehanna\u2019s Christopher Rolland was intrigued by the company removing the gross margin forecast from its annual outlook \u201cfor the first time\u201d and relegating it to \u201csmall font in the CFO presentation.\u201d Meanwhile, Intel gave more prominent mention to its operating margins. The company predicts a 3 percentage-point decline in gross margins for the first quarter and flat operating margins. \u201cWe believe this purposeful reporting change signifies a strong and sustained ramp in memory (multiyear) as a greater mix of NAND would be dilutive to gross margins, but potentially accretive to operating margins,\u201d Rolland wrote, while hiking his price target to $54 from $48. \u201cWhile the old adage is that \u2018Intel stock follows gross margins,\u2019 we find this belief somewhat silly as we feel EPS (or better yet \u2018owner\u2019s earnings\u2019/share) is a far better indicator.\u201d   Intel\u2019s outlook for the current quarter was generally in line with consensus views, but numerous analysts thought that this shouldn\u2019t be cause for panic. \u201cOur initial take is that guidance is conservative with the potential for upside,\u201d Rolland wrote. Instinet\u2019s Romit Shah added: \u201cIntel has a history of issuing conservative guidance.\u201d Still, not all were convinced of further price appreciation going forward. In a note titled \u201cGrowth Ain\u2019t Cheap,\u201d Oppenheimer\u2019s Rick Schafer wrote, \u201cwe are encouraged to see non-PC exposure tracking toward ~50% of revenue, but earnings and free-cash-flow leverage/growth remain limited, keeping us sidelined here.\u201d He has a perform rating on shares. Intel\u2019s strong quarter lifted other chip stocks as well, with shares of Advanced Micro Devices Inc. rising 3.4% and shares of Nvidia Corp. rising 2.2% Friday. Intel shares are up 33% over the past 12 months, while the S&P 500 index has gained 24% and the Philadelphia Semiconductor Index has soared 44%. Emily Bary is a MarketWatch reporter based in New York. Emily Bary is a MarketWatch reporter based in New York. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/intel-stock-soars-to-highest-prices-since-dot-com-bust-as-analysts-cheer-cloud-opportunity-2018-01-26", "headline": "Intel stock enjoys best day in years as analysts cheer cloud growth in earnings - MarketWatch"}
