{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Nigam Arora", "text": "Published: Intel has almost moved from ugly duckling to swan By The strategy of buying \u201cugly ducklings that are just turning into swans\u201d is especially attractive for prudent investors who see high risk in chasing the momentum but still want to generate high risk-adjusted returns. One way to learn the strategy is to explore a recent buy signal on Intel .  . Note the following: \u2022As the chart shows, Intel has broken out after . \u2022 The breakout is on heavy volume. This is positive. Breakouts on heavy volume may retrace but ultimately (not always) succeed more often than not. \u2022 This is a second successive breakout. \u2022 . Such breakouts are powerful and are often followed by subsequent breakouts. This is exactly what has happened. When you look at the target zones shown on the first chart, the call to buy Intel at that time has proven spot on given that the stock has since risen more than 25%. For those interested in more depth about the last call, please see \u201c .\u201d \u2022 When the initial call was made by The Arora Report to buy Intel at an average price of $34.01, the target zone was set at $56 to $58. At that time many analysts still had a \u2018sell\u2019 on Intel and had their targets in high $30s and low $40s. This pessimism among analysts provided the opportunity for astute investors. \u2022 Now that Intel has broken out above $50, the same analysts are raising their targets to around The Arora Report\u2019s original target. The Arora Report\u2019s very long-term target now is $64 to $66. Please be aware that since Wall Street analysts have become optimistic on the stock, there is more risk in the stock now compared with our prior buy signals. The best way to understand this is that when there is a lot of pessimism, almost everyone who is going to sell has already sold it. A little bit of good news moves up the stock because there are not many sellers. On the other hand, when many become optimistic like is the case now with Intel, some of the buying power has already been exhausted. \u2022 RSI shows there is more room to run. My conclusion is Intel is a buy on retracements. Intel has almost turned into a swan from an ugly duckling when investors look at the big picture. The first step is to getting the big picture right. After Donald Trump\u2019s election, I started describing a scenario of Dow Jones Industrial Average  . The second step is to stay up to date with the big picture. The fundamental scenario I described about a year ago is still intact. Now the Dow has moved over 26,000. There is significant risk in highflying FAANG stocks such as Facebook, Amazon.com, Apple, Netflix and Google parent Alphabet. In contrast, a stock like Intel that is just turning into a swan presents a better potential for higher risk-adjusted returns.   Meltdown and Spectre are the names given to two computer processor security flaws. When they were discovered, Intel stock was aggressively sold because Wall Street didn\u2019t fully comprehend the nature of the flaws. At that time, The Arora Report call was to buy the dip and hold on to the position. A bigger point here is that investors often sell first before understanding the real implications of a news item. Investors who can decipher the real implications make money because they are able to buy at better prices when the masses are selling. Investors who bought Intel on our original call are getting a dividend of 3.53% their buy price. Investors who buy now still get a respectable 2.41% dividend. Intel trades a forward P/E of 13.25. Nvidia trades at forward P/E of 51.71 and AMD at 35.97. Of course, P/E should always be looked at relative to the growth rate. Intel is a lower-growth story, but the stock is still relatively inexpensive. The fast money has been made, though the stock still has more room to run. For those who want to control the risk and use prudence, it is important to not buy a full position after this strong breakout. It is better to scale in and control the position size. The best time to scale in is on retracements. Another technique investors can use that can over the long run double the returns is to build a core position in a stock like Intel and then add trades with tighter stops and closer targets. Investors who are enamored with Nvidia and AMD but have ignored Intel may want to take a second look at the stock, especially on retracements.        Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Nigam Arora is an engineer, nuclear physicist, author, and entrepreneur and the founder of two Inc. 500 fastest growing companies. He is also the developer of the ZYX Change Method to profit from change by investing. The premise is that most money is made by predicting change before the crowd. Arora is the chief investment officer at The Arora Report and the editor of four newsletters that track the ZYX Change Method. Nigam can be reached at Nigam@TheAroraReport.com Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/how-to-judge-intel-stock-after-the-earnings-driven-leap-2018-01-30", "headline": "How to judge Intel stock after the earnings-driven leap - MarketWatch"}
{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Wallace Witkowski", "text": "Published: Stock has wiped away 2017 losses in less than a month amid speculation that Ethereum mining led to GPU sales By When Advanced Micro Devices Inc. reports earnings Tuesday, the results will hold clues about how cryptocurrency mining effected graphics-chip sales, and the forecast will give indications about the effects of flaws in AMD\u2019s other core products. AMD shares this year have been making up some ground lost from 2017, when rival chip-maker shares skyrocketed. Gains may have been muted, though, by the January disclosure of chip design flaws \u2014 Spectre and Meltdown \u2014 that shook the industry as a whole. When news of the exploits first broke, AMD , but has admitted that to the flaw.   Shares were volatile following reports that a  software patch to address the vulnerabilities , so AMD will likely provide more detail about its efforts, as larger rival  did Thursday. Intel proved that there is life after Spectre (and patch problems), after showing off results from the quarter just before the vulnerabilities were revealed.   Meltdown and Spectre will not have an effect on the actual results that AMD reports Tuesday, but cryptocurrency mining likely will. Analysts suggested the popularity of mining for ether, the , drove sales of graphics chips from AMD and Nvidia Corp.  in the fourth quarter. As cryptocurrency mining moves from hobbyist rigs to enterprise-level operations, some question as mining systems move toward a more software-based approach. AMD will factor any doubts about future crypto-mining sales into its forecast, along with concerns about the Spectre battle.    The 21 analysts surveyed by FactSet on average expect AMD to post adjusted earnings of 5 cents a share, up from 4 cents a share expected at the beginning of the quarter. Estimize, a software platform that uses crowdsourcing from hedge-fund executives, brokerages, buy-side analysts and others, calls for adjusted earnings of 7 cents a share.  Wall Street expects revenue of $1.41 billion, according to 21 analysts polled by FactSet. That\u2019s up from the $1.33 billion forecast at the beginning of the quarter. AMD predicted revenue of $1.35 billion to $1.45 billion, and Estimize expects revenue of $1.45 billion.  AMD shares are traditionally volatile after earnings. In fact, in the September-ending quarter. Shares rose 2.3% to $13.25 Monday and are up 30% for the year, following a 9.3% decline in 2017. In comparison, the PHLX Semiconductor Index is up 10% this year, and gained 38% in 2017, while the S&P 500 index is up 6.7% this year after a 2017 gain of about 20%.    Mizuho analyst Vijay Rakesh, who has a buy rating and a $17 price target on AMD, said strong stands to benefit AMD as well as Nvidia. \u201cWe believe it is key to understand that pricing reflects more of a stronger GPU demand and tight GPU inventory than a pricing tailwind,\u201d Rakesh said in a note. A lot of that is attributed to the ether effect, and Susquehanna Financial Group analyst Christopher Rolland said that could be a problem because a lot of those sales are at a significant markup and may be artificially inflating revenue.   In a note, Rolland said \u201cwe believe a scenario exists whereby GPU sales are artificially inflated as consumers buy premium gaming cards and use them for gaming 5% of the time and mining the other 95% to recoup as much of the upfront cost as possible.\u201d Rolland said that after about nine months, those cards will hold significant \u201csalvage value\u201d for resale into the used market, which could depress prices in the future. On Monday, MKM Partners analyst Ruben Roy, who has a neutral rating, from $13 and expects AMD to top Wall Street estimates and offer a strong forecast for the March-ending quarter. Of the 28 analysts who cover AMD, nine have buy or overweight ratings, 15 have hold ratings and four have sell ratings, with an average price target of $14.23, a 7.5% premium to recent trading. Wallace Witkowski is a MarketWatch news editor in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @wmwitkowski. Wallace Witkowski is a MarketWatch news editor in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @wmwitkowski. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/amd-earnings-mining-for-crypto-gold-more-spectre-details-2018-01-26", "headline": "AMD earnings: Mining for crypto gold, more Spectre details - MarketWatch"}
{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Wallace Witkowski", "text": "Published: Strong outlook gets boost from new accounting standard By Advanced Micro Devices Inc. shares rallied Wednesday after the chip maker showed strong growth in its computer and graphics business with a significant amount of that estimated to come from cryptocurrency-mining-related sales, but some analysts are still taking a wait-and-see attitude toward the company\u2019s turnaround. AMD shares were after the chip maker reported better-than-expected results, dropping at first up to 5% after hours before swinging to a gain, and stood as the most actively traded stock in Tuesday after-hours trading. On Wednesday, shares surged 6.7% to $13.72 for a gain of nearly 33% for January alone. In comparison, the PHLX Semiconductor Index is up 8.3% and the S&P 500 index is up 5.4% this month. Of note, revenue from computer and graphics products, which includes desktop and laptop chips as well as graphics chips, surged 60% to $958 million from the year-ago quarter. That\u2019s the segment which includes products used for cryptocurrency mining. That strength also translated into share gains for rival Nvidia Corp. , which saw its stock rise 1.6% on Wednesday.    Analyst notes from late Tuesday and Wednesday focused primarily on those estimated crypto sales; AMD\u2019s outlook, which utilized new accounting standards; and gross margins. Jefferies analyst Mark Lipacis, who has a buy rating and a $19 price target, noted that one-third of AMD\u2019s $140 million in quarter-to-quarter growth in computer and graphic revenue was due to cryptocurrency-mining demand, and that the other two-thirds was for gaming and desktop uses \u201cvalidating the strength of new product cycles.\u201d \u201cWe model AMD server share at 5% and 10% share exiting 2018 and 2019, and continue to view blockchain and cryptocurrency as longer-term growth drivers,\u201d Lipacis said. Mizuho analyst Vijay Rakesh, who has a buy rating and a $17 price target, said while attention is being paid to computer and graphics growth, investors are also concerned about traction in the company\u2019s sales to data centers and gross margin improvement. MKM Partners analyst Ruben Roy, who has a neutral rating and a $14.50 \u201cfair value estimate,\u201d adopted a more-wait and see attitude toward new product rollouts. Roy noted \u201cwhile we continue to appreciate AMD\u2019s execution, we still see the shares as appropriately valued at current levels until more clarity on the sustainability of new product growth can be attained.\u201d Susquehanna Financial analyst Christopher Rolland, who has a neutral rating and $13 price target, took issue with AMD\u2019s unexpected use of accounting standard ASC 606, which concerns reporting revenue from contracts. Rolland noted: While we believe 1Q18 guidance was likely a massive beat, also driven in large part by crypto-related GPU shipments after a record January, the company announced (without warning) the adoption of the ASC 606 accounting change, but refused to quantify the impact (this is not common practice as all our covered companies have quantified the impact), thus obscuring 1Q18 guidance. AMD had forecast first-quarter revenue of $1.5 billion to $1.6 billion, well above the then-Street consensus of $1.25 billion, which got a $100 million boost from the application of ASC 606. Oppenheimer analyst Rick Schafer, who has a perform rating on AMD, noted concern about the company\u2019s gross margin growth even with the introduction of new products. AMD reported a fourth-quarter gross margin of 35%, up from 32% in the year-ago quarter, but flat sequentially. Schafer noted: Consensus estimates called for ~13% FY18 revenue growth into the print, and margin leverage appears limited despite new products (Ryzen/Vega/EPYC) accounting for a larger share of revenue. Net, while commentary around new products (33% of 4Q revenue) appears positive, we believe the FY18 guidance serves as a reminder that AMD\u2019s turnaround remains early days. Stifel analyst Kevin Cassidy, who has a hold rating and a $13 target price, also was adopting a wait-and-see approach to margin expansion. He noted: Management\u2019s full year 2018 guidance for double digit revenue growth, greater than 36% GM and OpEx at ~28% of revenue is also above our prior estimates. AMD\u2019s revenue performance may be catching up to its share price valuation but we are waiting for evidence of significant GM expansion to justify the earnings valuation. Of the 28 analysts who cover AMD, nine have buy or overweight ratings, 15 have hold ratings and four have sell ratings. Before the report, analysts had an average price target of $14.23. After earnings, that rose to an average price target of $14.56. Wallace Witkowski is a MarketWatch news editor in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @wmwitkowski. Wallace Witkowski is a MarketWatch news editor in San Francisco. Follow him on Twitter @wmwitkowski. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "source": "MarketWatch", "link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/amd-rallies-on-graphic-chip-sales-outlook-but-analysts-focus-on-margin-growth-2018-01-31", "headline": "AMD rallies on graphic-chip sales, outlook, but analysts focus on margin growth - MarketWatch"}
