{"tick": "NVDA", "author": "Wallace Witkowski", "text": "Published: Data-center revenue, 2nd largest segment, expected to rise 85% By Data-center and auto-related chip sales will likely be the focus of Nvidia Corp. earnings when the chipmaker reports after the bell on Thursday. Outside of \u2019s graphics and gaming sales, data-center and auto-related sales are the fastest growing arms of the Santa Clara, Calif.-based chip maker. Gaming revenue is expected to rise 14% to $1.54 billion from the year-ago period, according to FactSet, but data-center revenue is expected to jump 85% to $548.1 million. Auto-related revenue, which was the , is forecast to rise 19% to $152.2 million. Recently, Nvidia to develop self-driving vehicle systems, and with , while the company\u2019s opportunities in the auto market. In those systems, however, that can be exploited by hackers. Also, data visualization revenue is estimated to rise 7% to $240.9 million, and PC and mobile OEM revenue is expected to decline 3.4% to $170.1 million. A focus on cryptocurrency mining-based sales will likely be acute given that a third of \u2019s computer and graphics chip revenue was estimated to come from . Investors, however, may start rethinking how relevant cryptocurrency mining is to both Nvidia and AMD given the recent selloffs in digital currencies. Bitcoin prices rallied more than 200% over the December ending quarter to end the year just shy of $14,000, after nearly reaching $20,000, but are now trading around $7,000.  Of the 23 analysts surveyed by FactSet, Nvidia on average is expected to post adjusted earnings of $1.16 a share, up from the 98 cents a share expected at the beginning of the quarter, and from 99 cents a share a year ago. Estimize, a software platform that uses crowdsourcing from hedge-fund executives, brokerages, buy-side analysts and others, calls for earnings of $1.27 a share.  Wall Street expects revenue of $2.66 billion from Nvidia, according to 26 analysts polled by FactSet.